Title : Daniel-Maurice Godefroy de Linctot
Text : '''Daniel-Maurice Godefroy de Linctot''' (baptized May 5, 1739<ref name=cdob/> &ndash; died between January 18 and April 30, 1783<ref name=harrison>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Madison/01-04-02-0203 |title=Benjamin Harrison to Virginia Delegates 27 July 1782 |publisher=U.S. National Archives |work=Founders Online |accessdate=2014-05-02}}</ref>) was a colonial army officer and merchant in [[Quebec]] and an [[Indian agent]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=cdob>{{Cite DCB |title=Godefroy de Linctot, Daniel-Maurice |volume=4 |last=Chaput |first=Donald |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/godefroy_de_linctot_daniel_maurice_4E.html}}</ref>

The son of Louis-René Godefroy de Linctot and Catherine-Apolline Blondeau, Linctot joined the army of [[New France]] as a cadet, becoming an ensign in 1759. After the French defeat, Linctot and his family went to [[France]], arriving in January 1762. He returned to North America and became a trader in the [[Illinois Country]]. Although he originally was considered a British supporter, Linctot joined the American militia in July 1778. He led a unit of horse soldiers in attacks against [[Peoria, Illinois|Peouarea]], [[Vincennes, Indiana|Vincennes]] and [[Lafayette, Indiana|Ouiatanon]]. In 1779, he was named Indian agent by [[George Rogers Clark]];<ref name=cdob/> the commission was confirmed by [[Virginia]] governor [[Thomas Jefferson]] the following year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Jefferson/01-03-02-0337 |title=Commission to D. M. G. Linctot as Indian Agent, 17 February 1780 |publisher=U.S. Archives |work=Founders Online |accessdate=2014-05-02}}</ref> Linctot helped recruit members of the [[Shawnee]]s, [[Lenape|Delaware]]s and other tribes in the [[Ohio Valley]] to the American cause.<ref name=cdob/>

In 1782, Virginia governor [[Benjamin Harrison V|Benjamin Harrison]] wrote to the Virginia delegates in [[United States Congress|Congress]] regarding unpaid salary and expenses for Linctot.<ref name=harrison/>

He died in the Illinois Country<ref name=cdob/> sometime during the following year.

